6/22/2026

Fixed pfSense log forwarding, fully set up Wazuh, and used SIEM to detect and triage a real attack chain

What I did:
-Fixed pfSense syslogd stopping periodically:
Noticed pfSense was stopping syslog forwarding to Wazuh every ~20 minutes
Restarting syslogd from Status > Services fixed it temporarily but it kept dying
Researched and found it is a known bug where syslogd receives a "Connection refused" message when Wazuh restarts and treats it as fatal, permanently removing Wazuh from its destination list
Fixed by adding two floating rules in pfSense under Firewall > Rules > Floating:
Pass rule: LAN outbound, UDP, source 192.168.10.1 port 514 to 192.168.10.50 port 514, state type None
State type None means pfSense does not track connection state so syslogd never sees a rejection
Block rule: LAN inbound, ICMP destination unreachable, source 192.168.10.50 to 192.168.10.1
Blocks the rejection ICMP from ever reaching syslogd
Restarted syslogd after applying rules, forwarding stayed stable

