What I learned:
-pfSense syslogd permanently stops forwarding logs if it receives a connection refused ICMP message from the remote syslog server, fixed with stateless floating rules that block the rejection
-Wazuh archives need logall_json set to yes in ossec.conf AND the wazuh-archives-* index pattern manually created in the dashboard before logs are visible
-Wazuh agents need read permissions on every log file they monitor, wazuh user must be in the adm group to read auth.log on Ubuntu
-Hydra is an online password cracker, -l is single username, -P is password file, it reports credentials when it finds a match
-John the Ripper is an offline hash cracker, it hashes candidate passwords using the same algorithm as the target and compares results locally, never touching the live system after hash extraction
-A SYN flood exhausts the server connection table with half-open connections, mitigated by SYN cookie protection at the Linux kernel level
-Alert triage workflow: alert fires, investigate source and context, determine true or false positive, document and close
-SIEM flooding is a real attacker technique where noise is generated to hide real activity, mitigated by correlation rules that collapse thousands of individual events into one meaningful alert
-Custom Wazuh rules must be inside a group tag, if_sid for the current triggering rule, if_matched_sid for prior rule correlation, same_srcip tracks frequency by source IP
-MITRE ATT&CK technique IDs add standardized framework context to custom detection rules and appear in the ATT&CK dashboard in Wazuh
-Building and tuning detection is engineering work, SOC analysts triage what the tools surface, engineers design and tune the tools themselves
